[[File:Knesset Hall.JPG|right|thumb|250px]]

'''Pray for the Peace of Jerusalem''' is a [[statue]] by the [[Israelis|Israeli]] artist [[Dani Karavan]] located on the southern wall of the [[Knesset]] assembly hall. Due to its location, this artwork is the most photographed work of art in Israel.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}

==History==
In 1964, in the age of 33, [[Dani Karavan]] was chosen by [[Dora Gad]], the Knesset interior architect, to create the statue that will consist of the western central wall of the Knesset assembly hall.

The statue is a scenery view, curved in stone, originated in [[Deir al-Asad]] quarry in the [[Galilee]]. The cartography is 24&nbsp;meters wide and 7&nbsp;meters tall. The statue in one out of two [[Dani Karavan]] art pieces, located in the [[Knesset]]. The second piece is the front wooden wall of the Knesset Auditorium

